2. Output (Printing to Screen)
Use cout to print things.

Code	Output
cout << "Hello World";	Hello World
cout << 5 + 3;	8
cout << "5 + 3";	5 + 3
cout << "Hello" << endl << "World";	Hello (new line) World
endl means "end line" - it moves to the next line.

3. Variables (Storing Data)
A variable is a container that holds a value.

cpp
int x;        // declares a variable named x that holds integers
x = 5;        // stores 5 in x
int y = 10;   // declares y and stores 10 in one line
Common Variable Types
Type	What it stores	Example
int	Whole numbers	-5, 0, 42, 1000
double	Decimal numbers	3.14, -0.5, 99.99
char	Single character	'A', 'b', '9', '?'
string	Text	"Hello", "Watermelon"
bool	True or false	true, false
Examples
cpp
int age = 17;
string name = "Alice";
double price = 19.99;
bool isStudent = true;
char grade = 'A';
4. Input (Reading from Keyboard)
Use cin to read what the user types.

cpp
int x;
cin >> x;        // waits for user to type a number
Reading Multiple Values
cpp
int a, b;
cin >> a >> b;   // user types "10 20" → a=10, b=20
Reading a String
cpp
string name;
cin >> name;     // user types "Alice" → name="Alice"
Note: cin stops reading at spaces. For "Elon Musk", it would only read "Elon".

5. Reading Strings with Spaces (getline)
To read a full line including spaces, use getline().

cpp
string fullName;
getline(cin, fullName);   // user types "Elon Reeve Musk"
                         // fullName = "Elon Reeve Musk"
Important Warning
If you use cin before getline, add cin.ignore():

cpp
int age;
string name;
cin >> age;
cin.ignore();            // removes leftover newline
getline(cin, name);      // works properly now
6. If Statements (Making Decisions)
Use if to run code only when a condition is true.

cpp
if (x > 0) {
    cout << "x is positive";
}
If x is greater than 0, it prints "x is positive". If not, it does nothing.

7. Else (When Condition is False)
cpp
if (x > 0) {
    cout << "positive";
} else {
    cout << "not positive";
}
If x > 0 is true → prints "positive"
If x > 0 is false → prints "not positive"

8. Else If (Multiple Conditions)
cpp
if (x > 0) {
    cout << "positive";
} else if (x < 0) {
    cout << "negative";
} else {
    cout << "zero";
}
Condition	Output
x > 0	positive
x < 0	negative
x == 0	zero
9. Comparison Operators
Use these to compare values inside conditions.

Operator	Meaning	Example (true)
==	equal to	5 == 5
!=	not equal to	5 != 3
>	greater than	5 > 3
<	less than	3 < 5
>=	greater than or equal to	5 >= 5
<=	less than or equal to	3 <= 5
10. Logical Operators (Combine Conditions)
Operator	Meaning	Example
&&	AND (both must be true)	age >= 18 && hasID == true
||	OR (at least one must be true)	day == "Saturday" OR day == "Sunday"
!	NOT (reverses true/false)	!isRaining
Examples
cpp
// AND: Both conditions must be true
if (age >= 18 && hasID == true) {
    cout << "You can vote";
}

// OR: At least one condition must be true
if (day == "Saturday" || day == "Sunday") {
    cout << "It's the weekend";
}

// NOT: Reverses true/false
if (!isRaining) {
    cout << "Go outside";
}
11. Modulo Operator (%)
The percent sign % gives the remainder after division.

Operation	Result	Explanation
10 % 3	1	10 ÷ 3 = 3 remainder 1
7 % 2	1	7 ÷ 2 = 3 remainder 1
8 % 2	0	8 ÷ 2 = 4 remainder 0
Common Uses
cpp
// Check if a number is even
if (n % 2 == 0) {
    cout << "even";
}

// Check if a number is odd
if (n % 2 == 1) {
    cout << "odd";
}

// Get the last digit of a number
int lastDigit = n % 10;
